(1, 1, '2024-02-13 08:13:55', '2024-02-13 08:13:55', '<!-- wp:cover {\"url\":\"http://localhost/PSWordpress/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/child-development-three-to-four-years.jpg\",\"id\":156,\"dimRatio\":50,\"layout\":{\"type\":\"constrained\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-cover\"><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-cover__background has-background-dim\"></span><img class=\"wp-block-cover__image-background wp-image-156\" alt=\"\" src=\"http://localhost/PSWordpress/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/child-development-three-to-four-years.jpg\" data-object-fit=\"cover\"/><div class=\"wp-block-cover__inner-container\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"placeholder\":\"Write title\",\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-large-font-size\">3-5 years: preschooler development</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:cover -->\n\n<!-- wp:greenshift-blocks/container {\"id\":\"gsbp-4189ecd\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-greenshift-blocks-container gspb_container gspb_container-gsbp-4189ecd\" id=\"gspb_container-id-gsbp-4189ecd\"><!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"child-development-at-3-4-years-what-s-happening\">Child development at 3-4 years: whats happening<a></a></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Emotions</strong><br>This is an important time in your childs emotional development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During this year your child really starts to understand that their body, mind and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/preschoolers-social-emotional-development/understanding-managing-emotions-children-teenagers\">emotions</a>&nbsp;are their own. Your child knows the difference between feeling happy, sad, afraid or angry.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child also shows fear of imaginary things, cares about how others act and shows affection for familiar people. And as your child gets more confident, theyll also get better at handling their emotions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Playing and learning</strong><br><a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/understanding-development/why-play-is-important\">Play is important</a>&nbsp;because its&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/learning-ideas/learning-baby-to-preschool\">how your child learns</a>&nbsp;and explores feelings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child is now more interested in playing and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/behaviour/friends-siblings/preschoolers-making-friends\">making friends with other children</a>. Your child might start to play more cooperatively in small groups. Sharing gets easier because your child understands the concept of mine and yours.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child is becoming more&nbsp;<strong>imaginative during play</strong>. For example, your child might play pretend games with imaginary friends or toys, like having a tea party with toys. Your child might also try different roles  for example, they might pretend to be a doctor or a parent. And at this age, its common for preschoolers to have&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/behaviour/friends-siblings/imaginary-friends\">imaginary friends</a>, although your child can probably tell the difference between real and fantasy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By 4 years, your child might enjoy tricking others and describing what happened  for example, Mum thought I was asleep! At the same time, your child also worries about being tricked by others.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child might be very&nbsp;<strong>curious about bodies</strong>&nbsp; their own and other peoples. For example, you might find your child looking at their own and other childrens genitals. A combination of natural curiosity and role-playing is usually a typical part of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/sexual-development/childhood-sexual-behaviour-4-6-years\">childhood sexual behaviour</a>. But if youre concerned about a childs sexual behaviour, its a good idea to talk with a GP, a paediatrician or another qualified health professional.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Talking</strong><br>Your childs&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/language-development/language-3-4-years\">language</a>&nbsp;develops a lot this year.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child&nbsp;<strong>learns a lot of new words</strong>&nbsp;by listening to you and other adults and also by listening to stories. Your child also shows more interest in communicating and might like to tell stories and have conversations.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child understands most of what you say and might guess the words they dont know. Generally, your child understands many more words than they can say.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Around&nbsp;<strong>3 years</strong>, your child uses sentences of 3-5 words, or even more. Other people understand what your child is saying most of the time. Your child also points to parts of pictures  for example, the nose of a cow  and names common objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By&nbsp;<strong>4 years</strong>, your child speaks in longer sentences of around 5-6 words or more. Other people understand your child all the time. Your child also understands most things you say and follows instructions with 2-3 steps, as long as theyre about familiar things  for example, Close the book, and give it to Mum. Your child understands&nbsp;<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\">adjectives</a>&nbsp;like long or thin and uses feeling words like happy or sad.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Thinking</strong><br>Your child is&nbsp;<strong>fascinated by the world around them&nbsp;</strong>and asks a lot of who, what, where and why questions. When it comes to understanding, your child knows about opposites like big/small and more/less and concepts like on, in and under.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your childs memory is developing. For example, your child can remember nursery rhymes and might even repeat them back to you. Your child is also starting to point out and name letters and numbers that they remember, and they can count up to 4 objects and sort them by colour and shape.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Everyday skills</strong><br>Your child loves eating&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/nutrition-fitness/family-meals/family-meals-tips\">family meals</a>&nbsp;together. And your child understands your family routine and appreciates special events, like birthdays.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child is also becoming more&nbsp;<strong>independent</strong>. For example, your child can feed themselves, put on shoes that dont have laces, undo buttons and do a bit more when theyre&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/health-daily-care/dressing/how-to-get-dressed\">getting dressed</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your child is probably toilet trained, and they might be able to do some daily hygiene tasks on their own, like going to the toilet, wiping poo from their bottom and washing their hands and face. But your child still needs your help and supervision with tasks like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/health-daily-care/dental-care/dental-care-preschoolers\">brushing teeth</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Moving</strong><br>Your child loves&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/play-preschooler-development/movement-play-preschoolers\">moving</a>&nbsp;and being active. Your child is better at walking up steps, riding a tricycle, throwing, catching and kicking a ball, running, climbing, jumping, hopping and balancing on one foot. With your child so active, its a good idea to look at how you can&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/safety/home-pets/home-safety\">make your home safe</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When it comes to using their hands, your child might be able to draw a circle or square, build big towers using blocks, and use child-safe scissors. Your child loves using crayons, pencils and paintbrushes, which is great because drawing and painting build your childs imagination.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At this age, your child might also:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>unscrew a lid from a jar</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>know their own age</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>know the names of some shapes and colours</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>hold a pencil and copy some letters by 4 years</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>dress and undress themselves.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\" id=\"helping-child-development-at-3-4-years\">Helping child development at 3-4 years<a></a></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Here are simple things you can do to help your childs development at this age:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Give your child plenty of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/getting-play-started/preschoolers-at-play\">playtime</a>: play is important for developing&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/play-preschooler-development/emotions-play-preschoolers\">preschooler emotions</a>, because it helps preschoolers explore and express feelings like joy, excitement, anger or fear. For example, you and your child could try&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/preschoolers-social-emotional-development/puppet-play-activity\">pretend play with puppets</a>&nbsp;.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Spend time&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/outdoor-play/outdoor-play\">playing outdoors</a>: this lets your child explore the natural environment, have adventures and test their physical limits. Outdoor play might include&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/videos/messy-play-helps-development\">messy play</a>&nbsp;in sand or mud, games of chasey or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/active-play/treasure-hunt-activity-for-children-3-6-years\">treasure hunts</a>. When youre outside, remember to be&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/safety/outdoor-sun-safety/sun-safety\">safe in the sun</a>.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Make time for&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/development/creative-development/preschooler-creative-activities\">creative and artistic play</a>: this might be&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/low-cost-play-ideas/collage-activity-for-children-2-6-years\">collage</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/learning-ideas/drawing,-scribbling-and-writing-activities-for-children-3-6-years\">drawing</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/low-cost-play-ideas/dress-up-games\">dress-up games</a>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/autism/school-play-work/activity-guides/roll-a-story-activity-children-disability-autism\">storytelling</a>. Musical play is another idea  your child might like to dance, jump around or make music with simple instruments.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li><a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/literacy-reading-stories/reading-with-preschoolers\">Read with your preschooler</a>: reading together, telling stories, singing songs and reciting nursery rhymes all encourage your childs&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/connecting-communicating/communicating/talking-play-preschoolers\">talking</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/play-preschooler-development/thinking-play-preschoolers\">thinking</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/play-learning/play-preschooler-development/imagining-play-preschoolers\">imagination</a>. These activities also help your child learn to read as they get older.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Do some&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/family-life/family-meals-cooking/cooking-with-kids-teens\">cooking with your child</a>: this helps your preschooler to get interested in&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/nutrition-fitness/daily-food-guides/preschoolers-food-groups\">healthy food</a>, learn new words and understand maths concepts like half, 1 teaspoon or 30 minutes. You can give your child simple things to do, like tossing a salad or putting together sandwiches.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item -->\n\n<!-- wp:list-item -->\n<li>Play games with your child that involve&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/behaviour/friends-siblings/sharing\">learning to share</a>&nbsp;and taking turns. When you play, say things like, Now its my turn to build the tower, then its your turn, or You share the red blocks with me, and Ill share the green blocks with you. Sharing is still hard for children at this age, so give your child plenty of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://raisingchildren.net.au/preschoolers/connecting-communicating/connecting/praise\">praise</a>&nbsp;when they share.</li>\n<!-- /wp:list-item --></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list --></div>\n<!-- /wp:greenshift-blocks/container -->\n\n<!-- wp:greenshift-blocks/video {\"id\":\"gsbp-7aab1cb\",\"src\":\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/275556745?h=150c91d9a1\",\"provider\":\"video\",\"postDate\":\"2024-02-13T08:13:55\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-greenshift-blocks-video gs-video video gspb_video-id-gsbp-7aab1cb\" id=\"gs-video-gsbp-7aab1cb\"><div class=\"gs-video-wrapper\" itemscope><div class=\"gs-video-element\" data-src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/275556745?h=150c91d9a1\" data-autoplay=\"false\" data-playsinline=\"false\" data-controls=\"true\" data-loop=\"false\" data-mute=\"false\" data-poster=\"\" data-provider=\"video\" data-overlay=\"false\" data-lightbox=\"false\"></div></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:greenshift-blocks/video -->', 'Preschoolers (3-5 years)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-world', '', '', '2024-02-13 14:50:13', '2024-02-13 14:50:13', '', 0, 'http://localhost/PSWordpress/wordpress/?p=1', 0, 'post', '', 1),
